	"explanation1": {
		"component": "Explanation",
		"content": [
			"<p>In French there are several words that translate the word '<b>in</b>'. If you are saying '<b>in</b>' <b>with a proper noun</b> i.e. a place name, you will see <b>à</b>, <b>en</b>, <b>au</b>, <b>aux</b>, dans le. The chart below shows when each of these is used.</p><table><tbody><tr><td>à</td><td>Londres, Cambridge, Marseille</td><td>towns, cities, villages</td></tr><tr><td>à</td><td>Singapour, Hongkong, Taiwan</td><td>islands and archipelagos without gender</td></tr><tr><td>au</td><td>Maroc, Canada, Chili</td><td>masculine countries beginning with a consonant</td></tr><tr><td>en</td><td>France, Suisse, Chine</td><td>all feminine countries</td></tr><tr><td>en</td><td>Afghanistan, Iran, Andorre</td><td>masculine countries beginning with a vowel</td></tr><tr><td>en</td><td>Provence, Nouvelle Calédonie</td><td>feminine provinces and regions </td></tr><tr><td>en</td><td>Océanie, Afrique, Amérique du nord / du sud, Europe, Asie, Antarctique</td><td>the continents</td></tr><tr><td>aux</td><td>Pays Bas, Seychelles, États-Unis</td><td>plurals</td></tr><tr><td>dans le</td><td>Cambridgeshire, Derbyshire, Pas-de-Calais, Colorado</td><td>masculine provinces and regions including the British counties</td></tr></tbody></table>"
		],
		"id": "explanation1",
		"titleText": "Grammar / Use of Language"
	},
